# TSDoc Documentation Standards

Always add TSDoc comments to every exported function, class, method, and interface.

## Functions & Methods

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD
/**
 * Retrieves a single article by its slug.
 *
 * @param slug - The unique URL-friendly identifier for the article
 * @returns The article document, or `null` if not found
 * @throws {NotFoundError} When the article does not exist in the database
 */
export async function getArticleBySlug(slug: string): Promise<Article | null> {}

// ❌ BAD — no TSDoc
export async function getArticleBySlug(slug: string) {}
```

## Interfaces & Types

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD
/**
 * Represents the shape of a portfolio project entry.
 */
export interface Project {
  /** Unique identifier */
  id: number;
  /** Display title shown on the portfolio page */
  title: string;
  /** ISO 8601 date string of when the project was published */
  publishedAt: string;
}
```

## Classes

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD
/**
 * Service responsible for managing portfolio project data.
 */
export class ProjectService {
  /**
   * Creates a new project entry.
   *
   * @param data - The project creation payload
   * @returns The newly created project
   */
  async create(data: CreateProjectDto): Promise<Project> {}
}
```

## Rules

- Always include `@param` for every parameter
- Always include `@returns` describing the return value
- Always include `@throws` if the function can throw
- Use present tense: "Retrieves", "Creates", "Deletes"
- Keep the summary line (first line) under 80 characters
